{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Log entries with the same trace ID are grouped together regardless of which microservice emitted them.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is the handoff between log ingestion/normalization and correlation. A unit test of only the grouping function can miss real mismatches in how service-specific records are parsed and forwarded.","test_description":"Feed mixed JSON logs from at least two simulated microservice sources through the real ingest + parse + correlate modules, then assert all records sharing a trace ID end up in one group even when `service` differs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The timeline view orders entries by timestamp, correctly handling clock skew of up to 500ms between services.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is primarily timestamp-ordering/skew-compensation logic in one boundary; no real OS/network/subprocess dependency is required.","test_description":"Call the timeline ordering function with crafted entries from multiple services whose timestamps differ by up to +/-500ms, then assert deterministic expected order and stable tie-breaking.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A latency spike (p99 above 3x the baseline) is detected and flagged in the anomaly report.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"You must verify both statistical detection and report flag propagation. A unit test of p99 math alone can miss wiring failures where detected spikes are not surfaced in the report.","test_description":"Run baseline and spike datasets through metrics aggregation + anomaly detection + report generation modules together, and assert that when p99 exceeds 3x baseline the anomaly report contains the spike flag.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Malformed JSON log entries are skipped without crashing the pipeline, and the count of skipped entries is reported.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is an error-handling contract across parser, pipeline control flow, and reporting counters. Mocking parser failures can hide real exception/continuation bugs.","test_description":"Pass a stream containing valid and malformed JSON into the real parse + pipeline + reporting path; assert processing continues, valid entries are still emitted, and skipped-count equals malformed-count.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The tool handles a burst of 10,000 log entries per second without dropping entries or falling behind.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Throughput/backpressure failures usually depend on runtime scheduling, queues, and I/O timing. Lower-level tests can pass while real process-level behavior drops or lags under burst load.","test_description":"Run the tool as a real process with production-like config, inject a controlled 10k/sec burst for a fixed interval, then assert ingest count equals emitted/processed count and end-to-end lag stays within an explicit bound.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.23,"System":0.73,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
